@gspencergoog I wanted to address your comment above about making ContextMenuButtonItem a widget, now that I've done some refactoring and exploratory code.  I'm coming to the conclusion that it's not feasible, but I'd be interested if you had different thoughts here.

The purpose of ContextMenuButtonItem is to provide an intermediate representation of the buttons before building their widgets, allowing:

  1. Button widgets to be built with knowledge of their siblings.  Some buttons look different depending on if they're the first button of many, or the only button, or a middle button, etc.
  2. Users to modify the buttons before they are turned into widgets.  Users may want use a different widget than the default but with the same label/callback, insert a custom button after the Paste button, etc.

Currently in my refactored PR, this looks something like this:

```dart
EditableTextContextMenuButtonItemsBuilder(
  editableTextState: editableTextState,
  builder: (BuildContext context, List<ContextMenuButtonItem> buttonItems) {
    // Here, buttonItems represents the default buttons for the current platform.
    // A user could modify those buttons in any way here before allowing them to
    // be built as full widgets below.
    return AdaptiveTextSelectionToolbar.buttonItems(
      primaryAnchor: primaryAnchor,
      secondaryAnchor: secondaryAnchor,
      buttonItems: buttonItems,
    );
  },
)
```

If I made them Widgets, it might look like this:

```dart
EditableTextContextMenuButtonItemsBuilder(
  editableTextState: editableTextState,
  builder: (BuildContext context, List<Widget> children) {
    // This looks nice, but the widget children are totally opaque.
    // If I wanted to just remove the Paste button, I couldn't figure
    // out which member of children to remove.
    return AdaptiveTextSelectionToolbar(
      primaryAnchor: primaryAnchor,
      secondaryAnchor: secondaryAnchor,
      children: children,
    );
  },
)
```

I could work around that problem by passing the children widgets as a specific type in order to allow their fields to be accessed, though that might start to defeat the purpose of just using widgets, and I still run into the problem from point 1 above:

```dart
EditableTextContextMenuButtonItemsBuilder(
  editableTextState: editableTextState,
  builder: (BuildContext context, List<AdaptiveTextSelectionToolbarButton> buttons) {
    // This would allow me to take a look at, say, buttons.first.label and modify the list
    // based on that.  However, remember from point number 1 above that the buttons
    // need to know their place in the list.  So I can't just remove the Paste button from
    // the list, I'd also have to rebuild every other button widget as well!
    return AdaptiveTextSelectionToolbar(
      primaryAnchor: primaryAnchor,
      secondaryAnchor: secondaryAnchor,
      children: buttons,
    );
  },
)
```

## Conclusion

It seems impractical to fully make ContextMenuButtonItem into a widget here unless I'm missing another approach.  However, in my refactoring I have moved lots of buttonItem logic into named constructors and generally hidden them away unless users need them.  By default, widgets like AdaptiveTextSelectionToolbar work on a list of `children` widgets.

I've refactored ContextMenuController so that it is no longer a singleton.

Previously, all methods were static and everything operated globally on a single context menu.  This was nice to enforce that there is only one context menu, but it meant that you couldn't know if a specific context menu was shown at any time.

Now, you show it by creating an instance, and you can use that instance to see `isShown` or to `remove` that specific instance without affecting others.  I also added `onRemove` to be notified if an instance is removed by someone else.  There is still only one static OverlayEntry under the hood, so it still prevents showing multiple context menus at the same time.

Example:

```dart
myContextMenuController = ContextMenuController(
  context: context,
  onRemove: () {
    myContextMenuController = null;
  },
  contextMenuBuilder: (BuildContext context) {
    return MyContextMenu();
  },
);
```

Is there a way to add dividers in between toolbar items? I tried something around these lines, but was wondering if there is another way.

```dart
        child: TextField(
          contextMenuBuilder: (BuildContext context, EditableTextState state, Offset primaryAnchor, [Offset? secondaryAnchor]) {
            return AdaptiveTextSelectionToolbar(
              primaryAnchor: primaryAnchor,
              secondaryAnchor: secondaryAnchor,
              children: getEditableTextButtonItems(state)
                  .map((ContextMenuButtonItem buttonItem) {
                return Column(
                  children: [
                    TextSelectionToolbarTextButton(
                      onPressed: buttonItem.onPressed,
                      padding: const EdgeInsets.all(10.0),
                      child: SizedBox(
                        width: 200.0,
                        child: Text(
                          AdaptiveTextSelectionToolbar.getButtonLabel(context, buttonItem),
                        ),
                      ),
                    ),
                    Divider(color: Colors.black,)
                  ],
                );
              }).toList() as List<Widget>,
            );
          },
        ),
```

@LongCatIsLooong About ButtonItem vs. widget: [Here](https://github.com/flutter/flutter/pull/107193/files#diff-a9680c8f968ad15d426a2929cc646ca042795ec16464e9fbae8213fc59ec1f61R246) is where AdaptiveTextSelectionToolbar decides the padding of its children based on the index and total number of children.  [Here](https://github.com/flutter/flutter/blob/8875040c9871a5538bf204f0a73874e04412da98/packages/flutter/lib/src/material/text_selection.dart#L261) is where this used to happen before this PR.

[Here's a commit](https://github.com/flutter/flutter/commit/5f65c540a67665ef1a0f79a79272a2bc688d390e) where I quickly got it working by turning ContextMenuButtonItem into ContextMenuItem, a StatelessWidget.  Besides taking `label` and `onPressed`, it now takes a nullable `child`.  If child is null, then it will build a SizedBox.shrink (really the point of this is to tell the AdaptiveTextSelectionToolbar to override it with the right button for the platform).  If child is not null then it's used as-is.

This definitely isn't fully fleshed out, but I wonder what your vision here is.  I think fundamentally I do need a way to specify the label/callback without specifying what the button looks like.  It's possible to do this using a single widget as in the commit linked above, but it feels forced as it is there.

